    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Goblet drums of Bulgaria and Yugoslavia, with a shell of baked clay and a single head of animal skin attached with fine hemp string, usually held under the left arm and struck with the fingers of both hands.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Tambores de copa de Bulgaria y Yugoslavia, con una concha de arcilla horneada y una sola cabeza de piel de animal sujeta con cáñamo fino, generalmente sostenidos bajo el brazo izquierdo y golpeados con los dedos de ambas manos.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bekertrommen met een cilinder van gebakken klei, 1 trommelvel van dierenhuid, vastgemaakt met hennepdraad; bespeeld door ze aan te slaan met de vingers van beide handen; Bulgarije, Joegoslavië.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052488/Etnomusicologisch Centrum</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>保加利亞和南斯拉夫的高腳杯形鼓，鼓身為烘烤過的黏土所製，單一鼓面則為獸皮製成，以細麻繩將外框和鼓面繫上，通常將鼓夾在左手臂下，以雙手手指敲擊演奏。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bechertrommel aus Bulgarien und Jugoslawien mit einem Korpus aus Ton und einem einzigen Trommelfell aus Tierhaut, befestigt mit einem feinen Hanfseil; üblicherweise unter dem linken Arm gehalten und mit den Fingern beider Hände angeschlagen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
